<p><b>Pier Paolo Pasolini</b> (March 5, 1922 – November 2, 1975) was an <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italian</a> <a href="/wiki/Poet" title="Poet">poet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Intellectual" title="Intellectual">intellectual</a>, <a href="/wiki/Film_director" title="Film director">film director</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a>. Pasolini distinguished himself as a <a href="/wiki/Journalist" title="Journalist">journalist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher" class="mw-redirect">philosopher</a>, <a href="/wiki/Linguist" title="Linguist" class="mw-redirect">linguist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Novelist" title="Novelist" class="mw-redirect">novelist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Playwright" title="Playwright">playwright</a>, <a href="/wiki/Filmmaker" title="Filmmaker" class="mw-redirect">filmmaker</a>, <a href="/wiki/Newspaper" title="Newspaper">newspaper</a> and <a href="/wiki/Magazine" title="Magazine">magazine</a> <a href="/wiki/Columnist" title="Columnist">columnist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Actor" title="Actor">actor</a>, <a href="/wiki/Painting" title="Painting">painter</a> and <a href="/wiki/Political_figure" title="Political figure" class="mw-redirect">political figure</a>. He demonstrated a unique and extraordinary cultural versatility, in the process becoming a highly controversial figure.</p>
